    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How does ashwagandha reduce anxiety?</summary>
      <p>Ashwagandha reduces anxiety through HPA axis regulation (lowering cortisol by 30%) and GABAergic modulation (withanolides enhance natural GABA signaling). A 2012 RCT found 600mg KSM-66 daily reduced anxiety scores by 69.7% over 60 days.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is KSM-66 and why is it best for anxiety?</summary>
      <p>KSM-66 is a patented full-spectrum ashwagandha root extract with 24 published RCTs. For anxiety, 600mg/day demonstrated 30% cortisol reduction and 69.7% anxiety improvement — the most significant results for any adaptogenic herb in a controlled clinical setting.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How long does ashwagandha take to work for anxiety?</summary>
      <p>Most studies show significant anxiety reduction at 30-60 days. Some users report subjective calming within 1-2 weeks. Full adaptogenic effects — stress resilience, sleep improvement, sustained mood stability — require 8-12 weeks of consistent daily use.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Is KSM-66 or Sensoril better for anxiety?</summary>
      <p>KSM-66 (root-only) provides balanced calm without sedation — better for daytime use. Sensoril (root + leaf) has a more sedating profile — better for evening use or anxiety with insomnia. Both reduce cortisol effectively. Choose based on timing needs.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can ashwagandha interact with anxiety medications?</summary>
      <p>Yes. Ashwagandha may enhance sedation from benzodiazepines, interact with thyroid medications, lower blood pressure, and stimulate the immune system. Consult your prescribing physician before combining with SSRIs, SNRIs, benzodiazepines, or thyroid drugs.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the correct dosage for anxiety?</summary>
      <p>600mg KSM-66 per day (300mg twice daily) is the most clinically supported dose, used in the landmark 2012 RCT. For Sensoril, 125-250mg daily is equivalent. Doses below 300mg show less consistent results; above 600mg shows no proportionally greater benefit.</p>
    </details>

